Or what if we could respond to the clear moral choice before us and make sure every kid who needs to can see a doctor, a therapist, receive medication because we no longer debate the authorization for CHIP or quibble about expanding Medicaid?

Like standing up not only for the Dreamers, but also their parents, who decided to leave a hometown, a country that they knew, a language that was familiar -- to come here, to choose us, to give their kids a better chance, to contribute to the success of our country.
But we’ve also got to think beyond funding the government for a full year (as high a bar as that might seem for Congress right now) and reach for something even bigger. Aspirational. Inspiring.

Those who serve this country in uniform expect it of us. Defense Secretary Mattis has talked about the damage done to the readiness of our service members when we fail to fully fund our obligations, and instead limp along under these spending-gap bills.

We can't run government by crisis, lurching from one 30-day funding extension to the next. We also can't neglect the moral questions before us, in the hope that someone else at some point in the future will decide them on our behalf.
